like we were lepers.

23:50.345 --> 23:52.347
And I didn't ‐‐
I didn't even remember them.

23:52.347 --> 23:53.890
I didn't think about them.

23:53.890 --> 23:56.810
I ‐‐ It's like
I blocked them out or something.

23:56.810 --> 23:58.603
Until my dad died.

23:58.603 --> 24:00.730
And, you know, I started
going through his stuff,

24:00.730 --> 24:03.149
and then I talked to my dad's
friend, and he was cagey and ‐‐

24:03.149 --> 24:05.276
I don't.
I'm...

24:05.276 --> 24:06.820
I'm probably
being paranoid.

24:06.820 --> 24:08.238
Or you're just
remembering stuff

24:08.238 --> 24:10.657
that you tried very hard
to forget.

24:10.657 --> 24:12.867
The brain
is an amazing machine.

24:12.867 --> 24:15.995
If there's an event or a loss
that's too traumatic,

24:15.995 --> 24:17.914
it has a way of
walling itself off

24:17.914 --> 24:19.624
so you can
survive the trauma.

24:19.624 --> 24:22.085
And then
here come the memories.

24:22.085 --> 24:25.129
They come back in fragments
and little puzzle pieces

24:25.129 --> 24:27.173
that then you have
to put together.

24:27.173 --> 24:30.426
And when that happens,
that hurts.

24:30.426 --> 24:33.304
And I'm not talking about
just emotionally.

24:33.304 --> 24:35.807
The body remembers
the event.

24:35.807 --> 24:38.184
The brain remembers
the trauma.

24:38.184 --> 24:41.688
And that ‐‐
that's a whole body ache.

24:44.607 --> 24:46.276
Thank you.

24:46.276 --> 24:49.946
Thank you for...

24:49.946 --> 24:51.614
The people who love me

24:51.614 --> 24:53.867
keep telling me
I sound crazy.

24:53.867 --> 24:55.910
Oh, Herrera,
you know what?

24:55.910 --> 24:58.454
For what it's worth,
you don't sound crazy.

24:58.454 --> 25:00.665
And sometimes
a breakthrough

25:00.665 --> 25:03.501
can look an awful lot
like a breakdown.

